WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.140 --> 00:00:02.874
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Welcome back for

00:00:02.874 --> 00:00:05.415
more cosmology on a rainy day.
You'll recall,

00:00:05.415 --> 00:00:08.780
maybe, what we were trying to
do.

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:15.883
We're trying to determine the
past and future of the

00:00:15.883 --> 00:00:20.340
Universe--which,
it turns out,

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:23.213
can be summarized by a single
number, namely,

00:00:23.213 --> 00:00:25.500
the scale factor of the
Universe.

00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:33.570
It's actually not a single
number.

00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:36.440
It's actually a function. Right?
It's a function of time.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:38.300
The scale factor changes with
time.

00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:41.651
So, when I make this grandiose
statement that I'm going to talk

00:00:41.651 --> 00:00:44.030
about the past and future of the
Universe,

00:00:44.030 --> 00:00:47.396
what I really mean is,
I want to determine what the

00:00:47.396 --> 00:00:50.090
scale factor is as a function of
time.

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:54.130
And so, that's just a standard
kind of a graph.

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:56.261
Here's the scale factor,
usually given the letter

00:00:56.261 --> 00:00:58.970
a.
Function of t.

00:00:58.970 --> 00:01:03.960
Here's time.
The present is somewhere along

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:06.799
this graph.
Call that now.

00:01:06.799 --> 00:01:10.806
And so, here's--and the
Universe has some scale factor

00:01:10.806 --> 00:01:14.089
at the present time.
And what we're going to do is

00:01:14.089 --> 00:01:17.606
we're going to call that--define
the scale factor at the present

00:01:17.606 --> 00:01:20.184
time to be 1.
We're just going to--that's

00:01:20.184 --> 00:01:23.303
called normalizing:
when you set--when you multiply

00:01:23.303 --> 00:01:26.921
something by some convenient
number so that it comes out to

00:01:26.921 --> 00:01:30.959
be 1 at a convenient moment.
So, that's just a definition.

00:01:30.959 --> 00:01:39.345
We define the current scale
factor to be 1,

00:01:39.345 --> 00:01:44.664
to be unity.
And so, there's a point here

00:01:44.664 --> 00:01:48.090
at--right now,
the scale factor is 1.

00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:51.659
We also know what the slope of
the scale factor is,

00:01:51.659 --> 00:01:55.300
because we measure that from
the Hubble Constant.

00:01:55.300 --> 00:02:00.480
And so, in an appropriate set
of units, the scale factor is

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.590
increasing at a rate of the
Hubble Constant,

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:10.080
which is, I think,
2 x 10^(-18) per second.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.356
So, if the scale factor is one
right now, then one second from

00:02:15.356 --> 00:02:20.199
now, the scale factor is going
to be 1 + 2 x 10^(-18).

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:23.620
So, every second,
it gets 2 x 10^(-18) bigger.

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:27.320
That's not a real large
increase and,

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:31.842
in fact, over the entire
history of humanity,

00:02:31.842 --> 00:02:39.414
it won't increase by that much.
Let's see, in a million years,

00:02:39.414 --> 00:02:45.508
there is something like--okay,
in 10^(6) years,

00:02:45.508 --> 00:02:50.940
there are 3 x 10^(7) x 10^(6)
seconds.

00:02:50.940 --> 00:03:00.140
That's 3 x 10^(13) seconds.
Multiply that by 2 x 10^(-18)

00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:11.260
and the scale factor increases
by 3 x 10^(13) x 2 x 10^(-18).

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:15.766
That's 6 x 10^(-5).
So, it still hasn't made a

00:03:15.766 --> 00:03:18.470
whole lot difference,
even a million years from now.

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:23.891
But, keep at it for a while,
and the scale factor is going

00:03:23.891 --> 00:03:28.074
to pile up and will increase.
So, we know that it's

00:03:28.074 --> 00:03:30.852
increasing.
And then, the question is,

00:03:30.852 --> 00:03:33.960
"Is this increase changing with
time?"

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.488
So, let's see.
If it doesn't change--if it's

00:03:38.488 --> 00:03:42.140
just a straight linear increase,
this is the situation in which

00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:44.319
there's no matter in the
Universe.

00:03:44.319 --> 00:03:46.581
So, the Universe is not slowing
down because of gravity,

00:03:46.581 --> 00:03:47.979
because there's no matter in
it.

00:03:47.979 --> 00:03:52.765
And that gets labeled with this
factor Omega [Ω]

00:03:52.765 --> 00:03:56.096
being equal to 0.
Let me remind you:

00:03:56.096 --> 00:04:00.724
Ω is defined as the density of
the Universe divided by the

00:04:00.724 --> 00:04:03.770
critical density.
The critical density is how

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:05.650
dense it has to be to turn
around.

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:08.770
So, another possible track for
the Universe:

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:12.400
we know it's expanding at a
particular rate now,

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:15.689
but it could slow down in the
future, turn around and fall

00:04:15.689 --> 00:04:17.939
back--could look something like
this.

00:04:17.939 --> 00:04:22.949
This is the case where Ω is
greater than 1.

00:04:22.949 --> 00:04:26.872
And then, the intermediate case
where Ω is less than 1,

00:04:26.872 --> 00:04:30.550
but not equal to 0.
It sort of does this.

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:32.775
It falls off a little bit,
continues to expand,

00:04:32.775 --> 00:04:37.175
something like that.
And this Ω less than 1,

00:04:37.175 --> 00:04:42.270
but still greater than 0.
Okay.

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:44.770
So, here's the goal.
We've got to figure out which

00:04:44.770 --> 00:04:46.415
track we're on.
At the moment,

00:04:46.415 --> 00:04:48.676
we sit here,
and we measure the Hubble

00:04:48.676 --> 00:04:50.855
Constant.
So, all we know is where we are

00:04:50.855 --> 00:04:52.720
and where we're going in the
short run.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:55.548
And what we want to do is to
figure out which of these

00:04:55.548 --> 00:04:58.269
possibilities the Universe is
actually following.

00:04:58.269 --> 00:05:00.807
And in so doing,
decide whether we're going to

00:05:00.807 --> 00:05:04.133
end up falling back together in
this Big Crunch or expanding

00:05:04.133 --> 00:05:07.328
forever.
And we talked a little bit last

00:05:07.328 --> 00:05:11.470
time about a kind of direct way
of determining this,

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:15.018
namely, measuring Ω.
This Ω factor is the density

00:05:15.018 --> 00:05:17.720
of the Universe divided by the
critical density.

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.712
You could, in principle,
go out and measure the density

00:05:20.712 --> 00:05:24.146
of the Universe.
You can compute the critical

00:05:24.146 --> 00:05:26.293
density.
You divide one by another,

00:05:26.293 --> 00:05:29.230
and you know which of these
possibilities turns out to be

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:31.470
true.
And that ran into trouble,

00:05:31.470 --> 00:05:41.930
as you'll recall.
So, direct measurement of Ω.

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:46.730
This leads to trouble in the
form of dark matter.

00:05:46.730 --> 00:05:49.680
So, the Universe turns out to
be full of this dark matter.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:53.259
If you add up all the
galaxies--the mass of all the

00:05:53.259 --> 00:05:55.980
galaxies, including dark
matter--so,

00:05:55.980 --> 00:06:04.636
mass in galaxies gives you an
Ω that's less than 1,

00:06:04.636 --> 00:06:10.353
that's around 1/3 or 1/4.
But there might be--you know,

00:06:10.353 --> 00:06:12.151
now that we've already
discovered that the vast

00:06:12.151 --> 00:06:14.379
majority of matter is something
we know nothing about,

00:06:14.379 --> 00:06:17.696
there might be more of it
between galaxies that we don't

00:06:17.696 --> 00:06:19.971
know about.
So, we want a different

00:06:19.971 --> 00:06:20.620
approach.

00:06:29.019 --> 00:06:34.084
So, here's something you can do
that's really quite a different

00:06:34.084 --> 00:06:40.949
approach to this problem.
Let's draw that plot up again.

00:06:40.949 --> 00:06:43.648
And so, here's now,
and then, there are these

00:06:43.648 --> 00:06:45.120
various possibilities.

00:06:50.779 --> 00:06:54.265
And it might go like this,
or it might,

00:06:54.265 --> 00:06:58.760
you know, fall all the way back
down like that.

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:03.358
So, here's something you can do.
Remember that you can look back

00:07:03.358 --> 00:07:05.800
into the past.
You can look into the past by

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:09.430
looking at very distant things.
And you see the light coming to

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:13.738
you from the time in the past.
So, you look into the past

00:07:13.738 --> 00:07:16.980
because of the light travel
time.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:25.449
And so, if now is here,
we can actually look at objects

00:07:25.449 --> 00:07:29.540
which were existing at some time
in the past,

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:32.269
back, say, here,
I don't know--by looking at

00:07:32.269 --> 00:07:35.380
things that are three billion
light years away,

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.814
or something like that.
And the question is,

00:07:37.814 --> 00:07:41.074
if you can do that--you can
figure out how far in the past

00:07:41.074 --> 00:07:43.019
it is, by the way,
that's easy.

00:07:43.019 --> 00:07:55.210
Measure distance and time in
the past is just distance.

00:07:55.210 --> 00:07:58.370
Miles per hour.
Which way up is it going to be?

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:03.728
Divided by the speed of light.
So, if you can measure the

00:08:03.728 --> 00:08:07.135
distance to something you know
how long--how far in the past it

00:08:07.135 --> 00:08:09.442
was.
So, that tells you where it is

00:08:09.442 --> 00:08:15.454
on this axis.
So, then, all you need to do is

00:08:15.454 --> 00:08:21.889
measure the scale factor at that
time.

00:08:21.889 --> 00:08:24.983
And you can see that if you
could do this,

00:08:24.983 --> 00:08:29.360
you would be able to determine
whether at some point in the

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.698
past you are here,
if the scale factor was low,

00:08:33.698 --> 00:08:36.305
or here, or here.
And therefore,

00:08:36.305 --> 00:08:39.593
if you made accurate
measurements of the scale factor

00:08:39.593 --> 00:08:43.261
in the past, you could figure
out which one of these tracks

00:08:43.261 --> 00:08:46.115
you're on.
And if you could figure that

00:08:46.115 --> 00:08:49.859
out, then you can infer,
if that track continues without

00:08:49.859 --> 00:08:52.649
some other form of physics
kicking in,

00:08:52.649 --> 00:08:55.580
you could figure out where it
will go in the future.

00:08:55.580 --> 00:08:59.309
So, you've got to be able to
determine what the scale factor

00:08:59.309 --> 00:09:03.039
was, which doesn't seem like
it's actually all that easy,

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:05.759
but it turns out that this can
be done.

00:09:05.759 --> 00:09:09.339
And the way to think about this
is you have to think about the

00:09:09.339 --> 00:09:11.570
redshift, the cosmological
redshift,

00:09:11.570 --> 00:09:14.665
in different terms from what
we've been thinking about it so

00:09:14.665 --> 00:09:19.517
far.
So, a different view of

00:09:19.517 --> 00:09:23.397
redshift.
You remember this is where we

00:09:23.397 --> 00:09:25.460
started, right?
We measured the distance to

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:26.860
things.
We measured their velocity.

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:29.135
We got Hubble's Law;
therefore, the Universe is

00:09:29.135 --> 00:09:31.655
expanding.
And as we were doing that,

00:09:31.655 --> 00:09:35.280
we had the idea that the
redshift is telling you

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:40.576
something about velocity.
So, one view is that the

00:09:40.576 --> 00:09:46.195
redshift tells you something
about velocity,

00:09:46.195 --> 00:09:52.730
and the velocities are all
moving away from us.

00:09:52.730 --> 00:09:54.899
And therefore,
the Universe is expanding.

00:09:54.899 --> 00:09:59.817
But you remember that the
cosmological redshift caused by

00:09:59.817 --> 00:10:04.032
the expansion of the
Universe--that velocity is a

00:10:04.032 --> 00:10:09.212
little different in kind from
the way we ordinarily think of

00:10:09.212 --> 00:10:12.295
velocity.
It's not--objects are not

00:10:12.295 --> 00:10:15.456
moving through space.
It's just, the space itself is

00:10:15.456 --> 00:10:17.919
expanding and that leads to some
differences.

00:10:17.919 --> 00:10:19.402
For example,
in principle,

00:10:19.402 --> 00:10:22.961
the cosmological redshift can
cause things that look like the

00:10:22.961 --> 00:10:26.520
velocity is potentially greater
than the speed of light,

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:32.203
and things like that.
So, the cosmological redshift

00:10:32.203 --> 00:10:38.570
is not the same as an ordinary
velocity.

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:43.419
And one way to think about what
the redshift is,

00:10:43.419 --> 00:10:47.980
is the following.
So, another view.

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:57.130
The Universe is expanding.
But a lot of the things in the

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:59.770
Universe are not expanding.
You're not expanding.

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:02.419
The galaxy's not expanding.
We talked about this a little.

00:11:02.419 --> 00:11:04.990
That's because there are forces
holding it together.

00:11:04.990 --> 00:11:07.974
The Earth isn't expanding
because its gravitational force

00:11:07.974 --> 00:11:10.662
holds it together.
I'm not expanding because the

00:11:10.662 --> 00:11:14.129
chemical bonds between the atoms
in my body hold it together.

00:11:14.129 --> 00:11:16.721
The galaxy is not expanding
because gravity holds it

00:11:16.721 --> 00:11:19.832
together.
But a wavelength of light

00:11:19.832 --> 00:11:24.629
doesn't have such a force to
hold it together.

00:11:24.629 --> 00:11:28.844
So, as the Universe expands,
wavelengths of light expand

00:11:28.844 --> 00:11:33.822
along with it.
So, this is another view of

00:11:33.822 --> 00:11:41.465
where the redshift comes from:
that wavelengths of light

00:11:41.465 --> 00:11:46.190
expand along with the Universe.

00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:55.028
That's an interesting thought.
So, the question is,

00:11:55.028 --> 00:11:58.823
"Why do we observe light from
distant galaxies to be

00:11:58.823 --> 00:12:01.373
redshifted?"
In this interpretation,

00:12:01.373 --> 00:12:04.799
it's not because these things
are moving away from us.

00:12:04.799 --> 00:12:07.788
It's because,
during the time between when

00:12:07.788 --> 00:12:11.360
that wavelength was emitted and
when we see it,

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:14.751
the Universe has expanded and
the wavelength has expanded

00:12:14.751 --> 00:12:16.664
along with it.
And, therefore,

00:12:16.664 --> 00:12:20.631
we see a longer wavelength than
we would have from a photon that

00:12:20.631 --> 00:12:24.295
hadn't been traveling as long,
because the Universe,

00:12:24.295 --> 00:12:27.769
in that case,
wouldn't have expanded as much.

00:12:27.769 --> 00:12:31.429
Wavelengths of light expand
along with the Universe.

00:12:31.429 --> 00:12:43.310
And so, when we observe distant
objects, the wavelength we

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:52.690
observe is longer than when it
was emitted,

00:12:52.690 --> 00:12:55.920
because the Universe has been
expanding during that time.

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:01.756
This is--yes, go ahead.
Student: So,

00:13:01.756 --> 00:13:03.282
if the Universe is expanding as
the light is traveling,

00:13:03.282 --> 00:13:04.610
by the time the light reaches
this Universe,

00:13:04.610 --> 00:13:09.748
will be somewhat larger than
when--than when the light was

00:13:09.748 --> 00:13:11.034
emitted?
Professor Charles

00:13:11.034 --> 00:13:12.381
Bailyn: Yeah.
Student: So,

00:13:12.381 --> 00:13:14.596
is the time--is the time that
we, you know,

00:13:14.596 --> 00:13:16.970
that we even have [inaudible]
in the past,

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:20.026
is that the distance divided
by--I mean, is that the original

00:13:20.026 --> 00:13:23.032
distance divided by the speed of
light or the-- Professor

00:13:23.032 --> 00:13:27.012
Charles Bailyn: Okay.
So, this is this complicated

00:13:27.012 --> 00:13:31.927
thing about, what do we mean by
distance in an expanding

00:13:31.927 --> 00:13:35.064
Universe?
And what you mean--this is a

00:13:35.064 --> 00:13:39.199
good question.
What you mean by distance is

00:13:39.199 --> 00:13:42.609
how much--okay.
So, the first thing to say is

00:13:42.609 --> 00:13:45.737
that cosmologists worry about
this a lot, and there are

00:13:45.737 --> 00:13:48.750
different kinds of distances
that can be defined.

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:51.256
There's the coordinate
distance, which doesn't change

00:13:51.256 --> 00:13:53.278
as the Universe expands.
There are other kinds of

00:13:53.278 --> 00:13:55.710
distances.
In the particular case of what

00:13:55.710 --> 00:13:58.830
we're doing right now,
the key way you measure

00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:02.019
distance, remember,
is the standard candle.

00:14:02.019 --> 00:14:04.917
So, you define what's called
the luminosity distance,

00:14:04.917 --> 00:14:07.370
which is how much fainter
something looks.

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:10.631
And so, basically,
distance is defined--so let

00:14:10.631 --> 00:14:13.240
me--this is kind of a
parenthesis.

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:17.234
What do I mean by distance?
Distance is defined by this

00:14:17.234 --> 00:14:17.910
equation.

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:26.176
So, what you mean by distance,
in this case,

00:14:26.176 --> 00:14:31.116
is how much fainter are the
objects you're looking at than

00:14:31.116 --> 00:14:33.679
otherwise.
And so, something that's twice

00:14:33.679 --> 00:14:36.559
as far away--what does that mean
for something to be twice as far

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:38.388
away?
It means the light from a

00:14:38.388 --> 00:14:40.679
standard candle is four times
fainter.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:43.984
And so, you define distance as
the dimming of light,

00:14:43.984 --> 00:14:47.029
because that's the way you
measure the thing.

00:14:47.029 --> 00:14:50.027
And then, you have to be
careful when you're doing this

00:14:50.027 --> 00:14:51.970
out in strict mathematical
terms.

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:55.043
You have to be careful that
that kind--that the way you've

00:14:55.043 --> 00:14:58.223
defined, you don't get confused
about which kind of distance

00:14:58.223 --> 00:15:01.559
you're working on.
So, that defines distance.

00:15:01.559 --> 00:15:05.641
Then, time, the lookback time,
turns out to be,

00:15:05.641 --> 00:15:09.457
more or less,
certainly for short distances,

00:15:09.457 --> 00:15:13.450
correctly defined as Distance
/ c.

00:15:13.450 --> 00:15:17.649
But you do have to worry about
this when you get into large

00:15:17.649 --> 00:15:21.850
cosmological distances and I
don't want to go into that,

00:15:21.850 --> 00:15:24.765
but the different kinds of
distances are related to each

00:15:24.765 --> 00:15:27.450
other in complicated ways.
Okay.

00:15:27.450 --> 00:15:31.296
So, this is basically back to
the question of how you get the

00:15:31.296 --> 00:15:34.470
x-axis on that graph.
I'm now talking about the

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.120
y-axis,
the scale factor.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:39.779
So, then, how do you measure
the scale factor?

00:15:39.779 --> 00:15:43.984
The scale factor--so,
the scale factor now,

00:15:43.984 --> 00:15:48.689
of the Universe now,
divided by the scale factor

00:15:48.689 --> 00:15:51.223
then,
when you emitted that

00:15:51.223 --> 00:15:55.970
wavelength, is going to be equal
to the observed wavelength,

00:15:55.970 --> 00:15:59.200
divided by the wavelength of
the light when it was emitted.

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:01.793
Because that's how much larger
the Universe has gotten,

00:16:01.793 --> 00:16:04.289
and the wavelengths have gotten
big along with it.

00:16:04.289 --> 00:16:08.918
So that's equal to
λ_emit plus Δλ,

00:16:08.918 --> 00:16:13.948
as we've defined it before,
over λ_emit,

00:16:13.948 --> 00:16:18.628
which is equal to 1 + Z.
Because the redshift,

00:16:18.628 --> 00:16:21.386
Z, remember,
is the change in the wavelength

00:16:21.386 --> 00:16:24.090
divided by the wavelength when
it was emitted.

00:16:28.169 --> 00:16:32.474
So, by measuring redshifts,
you can tell what the scale of

00:16:32.474 --> 00:16:36.853
the Universe was relative to the
scale of the Universe now,

00:16:36.853 --> 00:16:40.854
when that light was emitted.
Now, remember,

00:16:40.854 --> 00:16:45.379
I defined the scale factor now
to be 1.

00:16:45.379 --> 00:16:49.852
So, that means 1 / a is
equal to 1 + Z, or the

00:16:49.852 --> 00:16:54.627
scale factor of the Universe in
units where it's currently equal

00:16:54.627 --> 00:16:59.910
to 1,
is equal to 1 / (1 + Z).

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:02.440
And Z, you measure.

00:17:07.509 --> 00:17:13.729
And so, in principle,
you can measure both axes of

00:17:13.729 --> 00:17:19.036
that graph.
And so, if I now go back to my

00:17:19.036 --> 00:17:25.130
plot, you could measure some
points on this plot.

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:27.883
Now, all of them are in the
past, not the future,

00:17:27.883 --> 00:17:31.496
because you can't look into the
future by this light travel time

00:17:31.496 --> 00:17:33.878
trick.
But you could go out there and

00:17:33.878 --> 00:17:35.747
you could discover,
if you made,

00:17:35.747 --> 00:17:38.339
you know, really excellent
measurements,

00:17:38.339 --> 00:17:41.460
you could discover that there's
a point right here.

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:45.050
That a particular galaxy,
or whatever it is you're

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:49.299
looking at, is far away such
that the time back is this.

00:17:49.299 --> 00:17:51.470
And then, you measure the
redshift.

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:54.965
You get a scale factor.
And you could measure that at

00:17:54.965 --> 00:17:59.259
that time the Universe had such
and such a scale factor.

00:17:59.259 --> 00:18:02.336
And if you measured a whole
bunch of these things and they

00:18:02.336 --> 00:18:04.279
sort of lined up in this nice
way,

00:18:04.279 --> 00:18:09.213
then you might conclude,
well, the Universe is doing

00:18:09.213 --> 00:18:14.340
this, and you might then
extrapolate to determine what

00:18:14.340 --> 00:18:18.789
the Universe is going to do in
the future.

00:18:18.789 --> 00:18:23.358
And so, this is just the Hubble
Diagram interpreted in a

00:18:23.358 --> 00:18:27.927
slightly different way and being
looked at at a distance

00:18:27.927 --> 00:18:32.745
sufficiently far away that the
rate of expansion would have

00:18:32.745 --> 00:18:36.650
been different back then,
than it is now.

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:39.140
So, I'm going to draw it all
again.

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:42.130
Here's a.
Here's t.

00:18:42.130 --> 00:18:46.000
There's this.
Here's one of these.

00:18:49.300 --> 00:18:51.670
And here's this.

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:57.593
But, you know,
that's not usually how we plot

00:18:57.593 --> 00:19:00.859
the Hubble Diagram.
What we're usually plotting,

00:19:00.859 --> 00:19:04.264
as you'll recall,
is distance versus velocity,

00:19:04.264 --> 00:19:08.200
because those are the things we
actually measure.

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:14.846
Velocity is redshift, Z.
And remember that 1 / (1 +

00:19:14.846 --> 00:19:19.950
Z) = a,
or--let's see.

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:27.772
1 / a = 1 + Z
a / a 1 / a

00:19:27.772 --> 00:19:32.279
1 – a / a,
yeah.

00:19:32.279 --> 00:19:36.640
1 – a / a =
Z.

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:40.382
So, this represents the scale
factor, this axis,

00:19:40.382 --> 00:19:45.442
whereas this--what we actually,
usually, plot is m -

00:19:45.442 --> 00:19:48.145
M, which,
you'll recall,

00:19:48.145 --> 00:19:52.200
is equal to 5 log (D /
10 parsecs).

00:19:52.200 --> 00:19:55.837
And so, this scale represents
time, because distance can be

00:19:55.837 --> 00:19:58.722
converted to time,
because we know the speed of

00:19:58.722 --> 00:20:01.825
light.
So, this is a time axis in

00:20:01.825 --> 00:20:08.276
really weird units.
And this is a scale factor axis

00:20:08.276 --> 00:20:12.556
in really weird units.
But, you can,

00:20:12.556 --> 00:20:16.394
therefore, transform each of
these lines, which is scale

00:20:16.394 --> 00:20:19.882
factor versus time,
into an equivalent line on this

00:20:19.882 --> 00:20:23.164
plot.
So, the green line is the plot

00:20:23.164 --> 00:20:27.730
where the Universe just expands
and there's no mass.

00:20:27.730 --> 00:20:31.680
Nothing slows down.
So, it kind of looks like this.

00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:35.150
All right.
Now, what are the points?

00:20:35.150 --> 00:20:44.990
This is now in the time factor,
and up here is then.

00:20:44.990 --> 00:20:46.819
Okay, so, you're going from now
to then.

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:51.967
So, you're kind of sitting on
this point, looking back this

00:20:51.967 --> 00:20:54.978
way.
And here is scale factor

00:20:54.978 --> 00:20:58.694
a = 1,
and here's scale factor

00:20:58.694 --> 00:21:02.180
a = small.
Okay?

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:04.756
Because the Z is getting
bigger, therefore a is

00:21:04.756 --> 00:21:07.594
getting smaller.
So, what would the red curve

00:21:07.594 --> 00:21:11.869
look like on this plot of the
things we actually measure?

00:21:11.869 --> 00:21:16.188
Well, when it's close,
the red curve sits right on top

00:21:16.188 --> 00:21:19.784
of the green curve.
So, it kind of starts out like

00:21:19.784 --> 00:21:24.941
this, with no distinction.
Then, at a certain point in the

00:21:24.941 --> 00:21:29.780
past, let's see.
How do I want to do this?

00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:36.107
Let's pick a particular time.
So, that's a particular

00:21:36.107 --> 00:21:38.920
distance.
At that time,

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:46.432
the scale factor is smaller on
the red curve than it is on the

00:21:46.432 --> 00:21:50.380
green curve.
If the scale factor is smaller,

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:53.873
the redshift has to be bigger.
So, what's going to be

00:21:53.873 --> 00:21:56.598
happening, here,
is the red line is going to

00:21:56.598 --> 00:22:00.399
gradually diverge from the green
line in just the same way it

00:22:00.399 --> 00:22:02.996
does here,
in such a way that at a given

00:22:02.996 --> 00:22:05.950
distance--that is to say,
a given time in the past,

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:09.721
the redshift is bigger,
which means the scale factor is

00:22:09.721 --> 00:22:13.187
smaller.
And then, the brown curve will

00:22:13.187 --> 00:22:16.970
kind of do the same thing,
only more so.

00:22:16.970 --> 00:22:18.370
So, this is what we expect to
see.

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:22.323
This is Ω greater than 1.
Ω less than 1,

00:22:22.323 --> 00:22:29.269
but still greater than 0.
Ω = 0.

00:22:29.269 --> 00:22:32.769
So, all the Hubble Diagrams
we've looked at so far have been

00:22:32.769 --> 00:22:35.497
down at this end,
here, where they're all lying

00:22:35.497 --> 00:22:38.551
on top of each other.
But you can imagine that if you

00:22:38.551 --> 00:22:40.630
get out to big redshifts,
redshift of 1.

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:43.602
At a redshift of 1,
the scale factor is half of

00:22:43.602 --> 00:22:46.521
what it is today.
You're halfway back to the Big

00:22:46.521 --> 00:22:49.373
Bang in terms of scale factor.
You can imagine that these

00:22:49.373 --> 00:22:51.963
things would really look quite
different, as indeed they do in

00:22:51.963 --> 00:22:55.217
this little plot I've drawn,
when the scale factor is half

00:22:55.217 --> 00:22:58.313
of what it is today.
If the scale factor is 1% less

00:22:58.313 --> 00:23:00.626
than it is today,
you'll have a tough time

00:23:00.626 --> 00:23:04.700
telling these things apart.
So, what do you need to do?

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:07.539
What you want to do is measure
redshifts and distances.

00:23:07.539 --> 00:23:10.427
Plot them on this plot,
and see which of these lines

00:23:10.427 --> 00:23:13.099
turns out to be true.
What do you need to do that?

00:23:13.099 --> 00:23:16.300
What you need is a really
bright standard candle.

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:28.176
Why does it need to be bright?
Because you need to be able to

00:23:28.176 --> 00:23:30.910
see it at large distances.

00:23:34.700 --> 00:23:37.976
And the thing that happened in
the 1990s, and that has

00:23:37.976 --> 00:23:41.160
transformed cosmology,
is that we are now able to make

00:23:41.160 --> 00:23:44.670
these kinds of measurements all
the way out to a redshift of 1,

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:48.965
and in some cases, further.
And the particular standard

00:23:48.965 --> 00:23:54.720
candle we're looking at are the
so-called Type 1a Supernovae.

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:58.122
I'll discuss what these are
later on, but for the moment

00:23:58.122 --> 00:24:01.710
let's just take the point that
they're standard candles,

00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:03.390
therefore we know how bright
they are.

00:24:03.390 --> 00:24:06.164
And they're really,
really bright--absolute

00:24:06.164 --> 00:24:10.847
magnitude of something like -19.
So, they're as bright as whole

00:24:10.847 --> 00:24:13.707
galaxies.
In fact, they often outshine

00:24:13.707 --> 00:24:16.742
the galaxy they're in.
These are exploding stars and,

00:24:16.742 --> 00:24:19.357
as I say, we'll talk about the
details of exactly how these

00:24:19.357 --> 00:24:22.383
things work later on.
So, Type 1a Supernovae turn out

00:24:22.383 --> 00:24:25.016
to be these really bright
standard candles,

00:24:25.016 --> 00:24:28.339
and you can make this kind of
measurement on them.

00:24:28.339 --> 00:24:33.507
I have the data here,
but it's--I have to talk about

00:24:33.507 --> 00:24:39.790
one more technical thing about
the way the data's presented.

00:24:39.790 --> 00:24:44.482
Let's see.
Ordinarily, the way you tend to

00:24:44.482 --> 00:24:48.517
plot these things,
as I said, is you plot redshift

00:24:48.517 --> 00:24:52.140
versus apparent minus absolute
magnitude.

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:56.534
This is a quantity known as the
distance modulus,

00:24:56.534 --> 00:25:02.119
and it's related to distance by
the equation we had before.

00:25:02.119 --> 00:25:04.855
And so, then,
what you get is,

00:25:04.855 --> 00:25:07.685
you get this,
and you get this,

00:25:07.685 --> 00:25:11.553
and you get this,
as we've written it down

00:25:11.553 --> 00:25:14.788
before.
And the problem is that it's

00:25:14.788 --> 00:25:19.093
hard to tell the differences
between these lines because this

00:25:19.093 --> 00:25:21.819
is now being measured in
magnitude.

00:25:21.819 --> 00:25:25.200
The separation out here at a
redshift of 1.

00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:30.148
This is about--this interval
here, in magnitude--let me write

00:25:30.148 --> 00:25:33.365
it that way--is about--oh,
I don't know,

00:25:33.365 --> 00:25:37.490
a third of a magnitude or
something like that.

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:41.265
But this whole plot is,
you know, if you go all the way

00:25:41.265 --> 00:25:43.643
back to time 0,
this whole plot is,

00:25:43.643 --> 00:25:46.789
I don't know,
can be 10 to 20 magnitudes.

00:25:46.789 --> 00:25:50.569
And so, it's just kind of hard
to see these little differences

00:25:50.569 --> 00:25:54.129
between the things.
So, they plot it differently so

00:25:54.129 --> 00:25:57.700
that you can bring out these
slight differences.

00:25:57.700 --> 00:25:59.299
And what they do is,
they do this.

00:25:59.299 --> 00:26:03.940
They plot a quantity called Δ
(m – M).

00:26:03.940 --> 00:26:08.474
What's that?
That's the difference between

00:26:08.474 --> 00:26:16.003
the measured distance modulus
and the distance modulus that

00:26:16.003 --> 00:26:23.142
you would expect at that
particular redshift in an empty

00:26:23.142 --> 00:26:29.070
Universe.
So, m - M at a

00:26:29.070 --> 00:26:34.650
given red shift in an empty
Universe.

00:26:38.470 --> 00:26:44.090
So, what does the green curve
look like?

00:26:44.090 --> 00:26:49.567
The green curve is Ω = 0.
That is to say,

00:26:49.567 --> 00:26:51.825
an empty Universe.
