00:32:12.009 --> 00:32:15.687
The green one's a straight line
because it's just at everything

00:32:15.687 --> 00:32:17.898
equals 0.
But there is curvature on these

00:32:17.898 --> 00:32:19.930
lines.
Okay.

00:32:19.930 --> 00:32:23.590
So, the problem's obvious.
Here are the observed points,

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:27.510
and they don't go through any
of these lines.

00:32:27.510 --> 00:32:30.484
And you can first of--okay.
So, there are many things to

00:32:30.484 --> 00:32:33.920
say about this.
First, the error bars.

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:36.924
Let's talk about the error bars.
Redshifts are relatively easy

00:32:36.924 --> 00:32:39.733
to observe.
You can do that to high

00:32:39.733 --> 00:32:42.630
accuracy.
This distance modulus is more

00:32:42.630 --> 00:32:46.378
complicated.
There are two kinds of errors

00:32:46.378 --> 00:32:49.940
incorporated into these error
bars.

00:32:49.940 --> 00:32:53.887
One is measurement errors--that
is to say, how accurately can

00:32:53.887 --> 00:32:57.440
you actually measure the
brightness of these things?

00:32:57.440 --> 00:33:00.564
That's an error in m,
you know, how bright--how

00:33:00.564 --> 00:33:03.039
accurately can you measure these
things?

00:33:03.039 --> 00:33:05.521
They're pretty faint by the
time they're out at a redshift

00:33:05.521 --> 00:33:07.915
of .6.
But the other is how good a

00:33:07.915 --> 00:33:11.923
standard candle is.
How well do you know exactly

00:33:11.923 --> 00:33:16.109
what the absolute magnitude is
supposed to be?

00:33:16.109 --> 00:33:22.030
So, accuracy of the standard
candle.

00:33:25.130 --> 00:33:27.677
And that's an error in big
M, because you don't

00:33:27.677 --> 00:33:30.657
know--these things turn out to
have a little bit of a spread in

00:33:30.657 --> 00:33:32.579
brightness, and you don't know
that.

00:33:32.579 --> 00:33:36.506
And so, that's why the nearby
ones, these ones down on this

00:33:36.506 --> 00:33:40.025
end, which you can measure,
really, quite precisely,

00:33:40.025 --> 00:33:43.656
still have substantial errors,
because you don't know how

00:33:43.656 --> 00:33:47.157
bright the standard candle is
supposed to be to perfect

00:33:47.157 --> 00:33:49.646
precision.
And so, you can see that down

00:33:49.646 --> 00:33:52.259
below a redshift of .2,
down in this region here,

00:33:52.259 --> 00:33:54.512
you're going to have a really
tough time telling the

00:33:54.512 --> 00:33:57.762
difference between these lines.
Because the lines are separated

00:33:57.762 --> 00:34:00.654
by a tiny fraction of a
magnitude and the errors on

00:34:00.654 --> 00:34:03.003
these things,
on any individual object,

00:34:03.003 --> 00:34:04.940
is several tenths of a
magnitude.

00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:07.625
So, you know,
pretty much all of these points

00:34:07.625 --> 00:34:10.982
go through all of the lines,
and so, that isn't going to

00:34:10.982 --> 00:34:14.623
tell you a great deal.
By the time you're out in here,

00:34:14.623 --> 00:34:18.729
you're starting to get several
tenths of a magnitude difference

00:34:18.729 --> 00:34:21.553
in the prediction.
Now, the errors are still

00:34:21.553 --> 00:34:25.029
several tenths of a magnitude.
So, observing one such object

00:34:25.029 --> 00:34:28.781
isn't going to tell you anything
because, supposing I observe any

00:34:28.781 --> 00:34:30.950
one of these things,
I don't care.

00:34:30.950 --> 00:34:34.169
Here's an error bar.
And while it doesn't go through

00:34:34.169 --> 00:34:37.380
this line, that's only,
you know, two times the error.

00:34:37.380 --> 00:34:40.739
Two Sigma error for those of
you have studied statistics,

00:34:40.739 --> 00:34:44.604
isn't such a crazy thing.
And so, one of these points

00:34:44.604 --> 00:34:47.429
would not tell you all that
much.

00:34:47.429 --> 00:34:51.372
But on this plot,
which was published in 2003 and

00:34:51.372 --> 00:34:56.136
contains data up until about
2001, there are a couple dozen

00:34:56.136 --> 00:34:59.543
points.
Now, this line here,

00:34:59.543 --> 00:35:04.855
the red line with Ω = 1 / 4.
We already know that Ω has to

00:35:04.855 --> 00:35:07.863
be equal to at least 1 / 4,
because we've measured all that

00:35:07.863 --> 00:35:10.091
dark matter out there.
We added it up,

00:35:10.091 --> 00:35:12.885
and it comes out to about Ω =
1 / 4 or 1 / 3,

00:35:12.885 --> 00:35:16.827
or something like that.
And so, if there's nothing else

00:35:16.827 --> 00:35:20.506
in the Universe beyond what we
already know about,

00:35:20.506 --> 00:35:23.210
you expect it to be on this
line.

00:35:23.210 --> 00:35:25.665
If there is matter in the
Universe that we don't know

00:35:25.665 --> 00:35:27.789
about, you expect it to be below
that line.

00:35:27.789 --> 00:35:32.943
So, if you take the points at
redshifts greater than .2,

00:35:32.943 --> 00:35:37.582
the interesting fact is,
all of them lie above this

00:35:37.582 --> 00:35:41.309
line, and none of them lie below
that line.

00:35:41.309 --> 00:35:44.300
Now, each of them has a
different error.

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:46.515
But nevertheless,
the points are all above the

00:35:46.515 --> 00:35:49.125
line.
So, if the Universe truly were

00:35:49.125 --> 00:35:53.280
following this red line here,
then what would you say?

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:56.111
You would say that half of them
should lie above and half of

00:35:56.111 --> 00:35:58.702
them--and points should lie
above--below just by random

00:35:58.702 --> 00:36:02.015
chance.
So, this is throwing two dozen

00:36:02.015 --> 00:36:07.679
coins and having them all come
up heads because they've all,

00:36:07.679 --> 00:36:10.070
by random chance,
if the Universe is following

00:36:10.070 --> 00:36:11.929
this line, landed above the
line.

00:36:11.929 --> 00:36:14.480
So, you can figure out what the
probability of that is.

00:36:14.480 --> 00:36:17.177
It's--you know,
if there are 20 points and

00:36:17.177 --> 00:36:19.480
they're all heads,
that's 2^(20).

00:36:19.480 --> 00:36:23.480
That's about--a probability of
one in a million.

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:26.420
There was another team doing
the same experiment.

00:36:26.420 --> 00:36:28.347
They measured about the same
number of points,

00:36:28.347 --> 00:36:32.044
got the same result.
So, that's two incidences of a

00:36:32.044 --> 00:36:36.039
one in a million chance.
That's one in a trillion.

00:36:36.039 --> 00:36:40.902
So, random errors are not going
to get you back down onto the

00:36:40.902 --> 00:36:44.980
redline, much less there.
Now, look at the green line.

00:36:44.980 --> 00:36:49.030
This is an empty Universe.
Nothing in it at all.

00:36:49.030 --> 00:36:52.937
Maybe we're just totally wrong
and we've screwed up all the

00:36:52.937 --> 00:36:56.710
dark matter, and we've got only
two points below that.

00:36:56.710 --> 00:36:59.030
That's almost equally
improbable.

00:36:59.030 --> 00:37:03.499
And so, what we think is going
on is that this line actually

00:37:03.499 --> 00:37:07.744
goes above the green line.
And one current hypothesis for

00:37:07.744 --> 00:37:11.639
what such a line should be is
this solid line up here,

00:37:11.639 --> 00:37:15.528
which nicely goes through the
points in such a way that,

00:37:15.528 --> 00:37:19.911
kind of, half of them are above
and half of them are below--the

00:37:19.911 --> 00:37:23.882
way points ought to be.
So, this is quite strong

00:37:23.882 --> 00:37:27.576
evidence that,
in fact, what the Universe is

00:37:27.576 --> 00:37:32.560
doing is not going below that
line, but going above it.

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:37.880
So, what does that tell us?
All right.

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:39.929
Let's do this whole exercise
backwards.

00:37:39.929 --> 00:37:44.610
Δ (m – M)
versus Z.

00:37:44.610 --> 00:37:52.429
Here's the empty Universe,
and here's what we see.

00:37:52.429 --> 00:37:54.730
So, how does that go onto the
next plot?

00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:59.720
This is now m - M
versus redshift again.

00:37:59.720 --> 00:38:04.308
Here's the empty Universe.
And so, what appears to be

00:38:04.308 --> 00:38:08.494
happening is this.
How does that,

00:38:08.494 --> 00:38:16.460
then, map onto the scale factor
versus the redshift?

00:38:16.460 --> 00:38:20.580
Scale factor versus time, sorry.
Here's now.

00:38:20.580 --> 00:38:24.670
Here's 1.
Here's this.

00:38:24.670 --> 00:38:26.329
This is now still the empty
Universe.

00:38:26.329 --> 00:38:28.547
It's a straight line in this
case, and so,

00:38:28.547 --> 00:38:32.241
what is happening here?
If you go back and you look at

00:38:32.241 --> 00:38:36.532
a particular distance--that is
to say, a particular time

00:38:36.532 --> 00:38:41.646
ago--so, you're looking here.
The purple line here has a

00:38:41.646 --> 00:38:47.383
redshift that is smaller and
therefore the scale factor is

00:38:47.383 --> 00:38:53.869
larger.
So, you ought to be here, right?

00:38:53.869 --> 00:38:58.144
So, that's what we're
observing--the implication of

00:38:58.144 --> 00:39:02.760
which is that the future is
going to look like this.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:07.330
So, the Universe in this
is--Universe is expanding.

00:39:07.330 --> 00:39:12.375
We already knew that.
And the expansion is

00:39:12.375 --> 00:39:14.200
accelerating.

00:39:20.440 --> 00:39:24.530
Something is pushing the
Universe outwards.

00:39:24.530 --> 00:39:26.860
So, we had a thought all along.
What's going to happen?

00:39:26.860 --> 00:39:28.270
Gravity is going to pull it
back together again.

00:39:28.270 --> 00:39:31.170
It's going to be slowing down.
No, not true.

00:39:31.170 --> 00:39:39.150
The Universe is being pushed
outward by some kind of force,

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:46.305
by some kind of energy,
which has the characteristics

00:39:46.305 --> 00:39:51.541
of a repulsive gravity.
So, it's anti-gravity,

00:39:51.541 --> 00:39:53.407
if you like.
This is what the science

00:39:53.407 --> 00:39:55.059
fiction writers would certainly
call it.

00:39:55.059 --> 00:39:57.639
It's something that pushes
things away from each other.

00:39:57.639 --> 00:40:01.379
And this pervades the Universe
in such a way that it actually

00:40:01.379 --> 00:40:04.619
dominates the behavior of the
Universe as a whole.

00:40:04.619 --> 00:40:12.460
We give this the name dark
energy, and we have absolutely

00:40:12.460 --> 00:40:15.400
no idea what it is.

00:40:18.730 --> 00:40:20.400
But, of course,
as my colleague,

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:22.232
Charlie Baltay,
likes to point out,

00:40:22.232 --> 00:40:25.249
we never actually admit to
people that we don't know what

00:40:25.249 --> 00:40:29.106
we're talking about.
So, you observe this kind of

00:40:29.106 --> 00:40:30.224
thing.
You don't say:

00:40:30.224 --> 00:40:31.990
we have no idea what's going on
in the Universe.

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:33.730
No.
You say: we discovered dark

00:40:33.730 --> 00:40:36.679
energy.
Big triumph.

00:40:36.679 --> 00:40:40.680
And so, we have discovered dark
energy, and furthermore,

00:40:40.680 --> 00:40:44.900
we know something about how
much of it there is--namely,

00:40:44.900 --> 00:40:48.010
because we can actually measure
this curve.

00:40:48.010 --> 00:40:58.306
And so, you can ask:
what is the density of the dark

00:40:58.306 --> 00:41:05.407
energy compared to matter?
Now, you know how to compare

00:41:05.407 --> 00:41:06.699
energy to matter,
right?

00:41:06.699 --> 00:41:08.610
You have to use E =
mc^(2).

00:41:08.610 --> 00:41:14.298
So, if you have energy--some
amount of energy per meter

00:41:14.298 --> 00:41:20.514
cubed, you can transform that
into energy / c^(2) per

00:41:20.514 --> 00:41:24.614
meter cubed,
and that now is in the same

00:41:24.614 --> 00:41:29.208
units as a matter density.
And so, you can have Ω of the

00:41:29.208 --> 00:41:32.621
matter, which we think is about
1 / 3, or 1 / 4,

00:41:32.621 --> 00:41:36.586
or something like that.
And you can ask:

00:41:36.586 --> 00:41:40.969
how much energy is there.
You can ask:

00:41:40.969 --> 00:41:45.430
how much Ω is there in energy,
in this dark energy?

00:41:45.430 --> 00:41:47.758
Not photons.
Not ordinary kinds of energy,

00:41:47.758 --> 00:41:50.359
but this repulsive--this
mysterious, repulsive dark

00:41:50.359 --> 00:41:53.196
energy.
It's about three times the

00:41:53.196 --> 00:41:58.186
amount of matter--where Ω,
remember, is equal to density

00:41:58.186 --> 00:42:01.396
over the critical density,
and, you know,

00:42:01.396 --> 00:42:03.993
it doesn't matter whether it's
an energy density divided by

00:42:03.993 --> 00:42:06.100
c^(2),
or some amount of matter.

00:42:06.100 --> 00:42:09.344
Okay.
That's what we think the

00:42:09.344 --> 00:42:13.315
Universe consists of.
So, here is the famous pie

00:42:13.315 --> 00:42:18.230
chart of the Universe,
which tells you what's going

00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:20.260
on.
So, you know how pie charts

00:42:20.260 --> 00:42:23.349
work?
You start with a circle.

00:42:23.349 --> 00:42:29.059
That's everything,
and here's us.

00:42:29.059 --> 00:42:34.460
So, this is all ordinary
matter, and all ordinary kinds

00:42:34.460 --> 00:42:37.760
of energy, photons,
what have you,

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:42.946
that we know about.
And it's something like 4% of

00:42:42.946 --> 00:42:46.612
the Universe.
Then, there's a big chunk

00:42:46.612 --> 00:42:48.430
that's dark matter.

00:42:53.340 --> 00:42:54.849
And that, we discussed last
time.

00:42:54.849 --> 00:42:57.790
The dark matter is this stuff
we can't see.

00:42:57.790 --> 00:42:59.597
It might be WIMPs.
It might be MACHOs,

00:42:59.597 --> 00:43:01.384
we don't know.
We can't see it,

00:43:01.384 --> 00:43:03.789
but we know it's there.
Why do we know it's there?

00:43:03.789 --> 00:43:07.273
Because it exerts gravitational
force on galaxies and stars in

00:43:07.273 --> 00:43:10.928
galaxies, and we can measure how
much of them there is by looking

00:43:10.928 --> 00:43:13.670
at stars--galaxies and clusters
of galaxies,

00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:16.848
and inferring the mass of them
by observing the orbits of

00:43:16.848 --> 00:43:19.470
things around them,
just as we did with black holes;

00:43:19.470 --> 00:43:22.471
just as we did with planets.
This is a fairly

00:43:22.471 --> 00:43:25.949
straightforward astronomical
technique.

00:43:25.949 --> 00:43:31.977
The rest of it--this region,
here, is dark energy,

00:43:31.977 --> 00:43:37.389
which not only can we not
detect directly,

00:43:37.389 --> 00:43:41.962
but it has a physical effect
unlike anything else we know

00:43:41.962 --> 00:43:45.800
anything about at all--namely,
it pushes out.

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:52.287
It's a purely repulsive force
of some kind and that purely

00:43:52.287 --> 00:43:59.800
repulsive force provides 3/4 of
the mass energy of the Universe.

00:43:59.800 --> 00:44:02.635
Well, that's bad,
because we have even less

00:44:02.635 --> 00:44:06.214
idea--oh, and I should say--So,
we've been counting up

00:44:06.214 --> 00:44:09.050
frontiers and controversies with
time.

00:44:09.050 --> 00:44:12.239
This is Frontiers and
Controversies in 2007.

00:44:12.239 --> 00:44:14.550
What the heck is going on with
this pie chart?

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:18.680
What's this?
What's this and why?

00:44:18.680 --> 00:44:23.582
That's what we need to find out.
Now, oddly enough,

00:44:23.582 --> 00:44:27.510
it turns out,
Einstein predicted this.

00:44:27.510 --> 00:44:30.732
Einstein was a genius.
Only, he then retracted it and

00:44:30.732 --> 00:44:34.409
decided it was the greatest
mistake he had ever made.

00:44:34.409 --> 00:44:36.718
And then, because he said it
was a great mistake,

00:44:36.718 --> 00:44:38.690
everybody ignored it for
seventy years,

00:44:38.690 --> 00:44:40.501
until we discovered the dark
energy, and then,

00:44:40.501 --> 00:44:41.710
somebody said:
oh, you know,

00:44:41.710 --> 00:44:44.070
Einstein told us about this
already.

00:44:44.070 --> 00:44:51.325
And here's how--why he did it.
Remember, Einstein wanted a

00:44:51.325 --> 00:44:56.809
static Universe.
This is before Hubble

00:44:56.809 --> 00:45:01.670
discovered that the Universe was
expanding.

00:45:01.670 --> 00:45:03.829
And so, Einstein was looking at
the implications of his

00:45:03.829 --> 00:45:06.349
equations of general relativity,
and he thought it would be nice

00:45:06.349 --> 00:45:08.503
if the Universe was static.
And the problem is,

00:45:08.503 --> 00:45:11.579
there's all this matter in the
Universe, so it attracts itself.

00:45:11.579 --> 00:45:14.230
So, it can't be static,
because if you try and hold it

00:45:14.230 --> 00:45:15.829
in one place,
it'll fall down.

00:45:15.829 --> 00:45:19.451
It has to either be expanding
up or expanding down,

00:45:19.451 --> 00:45:23.289
just like the pen is either
going up or going down.

00:45:23.289 --> 00:45:24.530
But that's bad,
thought Einstein,

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:28.779
because it ought to be static.
So, he invented an additional

00:45:28.779 --> 00:45:33.553
term for his equation,
which he wrote down as a

00:45:33.553 --> 00:45:38.327
capital lambda [Λ]
and called the cosmological

00:45:38.327 --> 00:45:43.661
constant.
And this had generated a

00:45:43.661 --> 00:45:52.557
repulsive force that would
balance gravity and lead to a

00:45:52.557 --> 00:45:56.657
static Universe.
And it was allowed in the

00:45:56.657 --> 00:45:58.530
equations.
It fit fine into the equations.

00:45:58.530 --> 00:46:01.477
There was no problem there.
Those of you who have done

00:46:01.477 --> 00:46:05.532
calculus, this shows up as a
constant of integration,

00:46:05.532 --> 00:46:08.340
so, it can be any value you
like.

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:11.100
If you don't know calculus,
ignore that last sentence.

00:46:11.100 --> 00:46:14.331
Okay.
And so, he invented this

00:46:14.331 --> 00:46:16.718
repulsive force,
this cosmological constant,

00:46:16.718 --> 00:46:19.493
to balance gravity,
so that you could have a static

00:46:19.493 --> 00:46:23.634
Universe.
Then, Hubble discovers that the

00:46:23.634 --> 00:46:28.409
Universe isn't static--discovers
expansion.

00:46:28.409 --> 00:46:32.643
And Einstein says:
damn, I could have predicted

00:46:32.643 --> 00:46:36.599
that, and then,
I would have been famous.

00:46:36.599 --> 00:46:43.780
So, Einstein says:
Λ was my biggest mistake.

00:46:43.780 --> 00:46:46.474
Because if he hadn't been so
insistent that the Universe

00:46:46.474 --> 00:46:48.881
needed to turn out to be static,
he could have said,

00:46:48.881 --> 00:46:51.260
you know, my equations predict
that the Universe either has to

00:46:51.260 --> 00:46:53.750
be expanding or contracting.
It has to be moving around.

00:46:53.750 --> 00:46:57.793
And then, Hubble would have
verified Einstein's prediction

00:46:57.793 --> 00:47:02.050
and Einstein might have won the
Nobel Prize, or something.

00:47:02.050 --> 00:47:06.299
So, Λ was my biggest mistake.
Except, it turns out that it

00:47:06.299 --> 00:47:09.753
might be true.
So, this is one of those

00:47:09.753 --> 00:47:18.822
fables, right?
The fable of Einstein's biggest

00:47:18.822 --> 00:47:22.915
mistake.
And the moral is:

00:47:22.915 --> 00:47:29.501
interesting ideas can turn up
in a different context and turn

00:47:29.501 --> 00:47:36.087
out to be even more important
than you thought they were--can

00:47:36.087 --> 00:47:40.745
turn up in other contexts.
So, for seventy years,

00:47:40.745 --> 00:47:43.713
you know, the idea of this Λ
term, this cosmological

00:47:43.713 --> 00:47:46.510
constant, was kind of buried in
